<paragraph id="8FD0E11ACE3DAF73CB0B83CABE6D7324" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="261FD4E5190526F3460E77DFEB306022" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F09EC0B3964CEB88A3CF6D8917FE215C" captionStart="Figure 98" captionStartId="F98" captionText="Figure 98. Distribution of Conostegia pittieri." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure98" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96456" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">98</figureCitation>
). In cloud forests from southern Nicaragua through central and northern Costa Rica to northwestern Panama, (500-)1000-2400 m.
</paragraph>
<caption id="C6EC3F3A0D1C382C05887E6F8F748A0E" ID-Zenodo-Dep="974237" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure98" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96456" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" start="Figure 98" startId="F98">
<paragraph id="F70D345E3E5528A616F16D59062DBB40" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis id="1BDA17CB7CAD7C5BEF96491A02C14043" bold="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Figure 98.</emphasis>
Distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="19D31FF75DEE4AAF896FD30814BA522F" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia pittieri" order="Myrtales" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pittieri">
<emphasis id="8DB2EAEBB245E40B40FDB34C5371795C" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Conostegia pittieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="1BC681FF17350CC9B9823AC2A24E5BC8" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<taxonomicName id="69C180BB61ABE5296C957230D6189EBE" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia pittieri" order="Myrtales" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pittieri">
<emphasis id="8BAC21EE358C9868BAC6CD1C256BA0FF" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Conostegia pittieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the few species of 
<taxonomicName id="D0322845A3F61E5A206764CAFBF5AFFC" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia" order="Myrtales" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2052D34A5A996A73749FFE9FB671425E" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Conostegia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that retains its petals once the stamens and style have fallen. The functional significance of petal retention, if any, might have to do with continuing to make inflorescences attractive (
<bibRefCitation id="258CAE65996BB1DC3F57F488EF2DD761" author="Bertin, R" journalOrPublisher="Evolutionary Theory" pageId="240" pageNumber="241" pagination="25 - 32" refId="B15" refString="Bertin, R, 1982. The evolution and maintenance of andromonoecy. Evolutionary Theory 6: 25 - 32" title="The evolution and maintenance of andromonoecy." volume="6" year="1982">Bertin 1982</bibRefCitation>
).The similar species 
<taxonomicName id="9D7EC40D1CC142CA78874C200B82CC6B" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Gleason" authorityYear="1941" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia chiriquensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chiriquensis">
<emphasis id="C36A981CDD6E687FE5F7748E93332BBF" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Conostegia chiriquensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also retains the petals and the style after the stamens have fallen. See the discussion under the latter species for differences between 
<taxonomicName id="00770DA113DF3658F21627D7302D5FC9" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Gleason" authorityYear="1941" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia chiriquensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chiriquensis">
<emphasis id="3936974F465B0F217CEE103E5F6F76D0" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Conostegia chiriquensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="8BD3256B2A0124A3B2885BB962CCF1F0" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia pittieri" order="Myrtales" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pittieri">
<emphasis id="20455F6F3BA32AAD119D6ECB5B596FF4" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Conostegia pittieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="DD1E13BA45F7D2206BB9F762A9022F91" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia pittieri" order="Myrtales" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pittieri">
<emphasis id="B429B8745085C715E1E6CD7DE0C369BF" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Conostegia pittieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been observed to be buzzed by female 
<taxonomicName id="A4A896CE4AF98239B0FA1AE9AD9ED7EB" class="Hexapoda" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bombus volluceloides" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="volluceloides">
<emphasis id="D12422897D3814BCDE446B391939D56E" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Bombus volluceloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(pers. obs.). As 
<bibRefCitation id="B8E181DBBFF2C256C7A2E6E16D272063" author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned, this species can be quite abundant in pastures and second growth but is rare inside the forest where it occurs mainly in riparian habitats. Individuals within the forest produce much less flowers (pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
